article.headline: Indiana wins fourth straight at home
article.linkText: Miller's last-second 3-point play lifts Fever over Liberty
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Kelly Miller knew she didn't have much time.

The Indiana Fever guard took an inbounds pass with 4.9 seconds
to play, drove to the basket and hit a short jumper just as the
buzzer sounded Friday night. After reviewing video of the shot,
officials ruled the basket was good and that Miller had been fouled
by Shameka Christon with 0.9 second to play.

She then hit the free throw to seal the 62-59 victory over the
New York Liberty.

"We work on that play a lot in practice," said Miller, who
finished with 12 points. "It was something we felt comfortable
with."

The winning basket took some adjusting for Miller to get in
position for the shot.

"I'm a righty, so I did have to switch it (the ball)," she
said. "I think the fact that I knew they didn't want to foul us
and put us on the line (helped), and I knew we didn't want to
settle for an outside shot."

New York, which overcame a 14-point first-half deficit, took the
lead three times in the second half. Ann Wauters led the comeback
with 12 of her season-high 19 points in the second half. Vickie
Johnson was also in double figures with 12 points and Christon
added 11 for New York (2-4), which lost to the Fever for the eighth
time in the past 10 games.

Kelly Schumacher also had 12 points for the Fever (5-3).

"In the second half, we did a nice job and we were in the game
finally," Wauters said. "When it comes down to the last play like
that, it's tough to take."

Indiana built its big lead by shooting 56.7 percent (17-of-30)
in the first half. But the Fever made only 7-of-27 attempts in the
second half as the Liberty fought their way back.

New York took its last lead at 51-48 on a basket by Wauters.
Indiana then scored seven consecutive points, all on free throws.

The Fever opened a 59-53 lead, but New York tied the game on a
lay-up by Wauters and Becky Hammon's two free throws and a layup
with 30.6 seconds to go.

Indiana, undefeated in four home games this season, tried
holding the ball for a final shot but officials called a double
foul with 4.9 seconds remaining, giving the ball back to the Fever
on the sideline near their basket to set up the winning shot.

Indiana won despite a cold night for Tamika Catchings, who
finished with 6 points and made just 1-of-12 shots from the field.

"Tamika is playing well. She is getting assists and rebounds,"
Indiana coach Brian Winters said. "Her shooting is not there right
now. But it a sign of a good team when we win and Tamika has an off
shooting night."

Indiana led by nine when Catchings made her only basket 13
seconds into the second half. The Liberty then rattled off 11
straight points to take their first lead of the game at 41-40.

"We calmed down the second half," New York coach Pat Coyle
said. "We started getting shots that we could make."
